1. **Initialization and Setup:**
   - `>`: Move the pointer to the second cell.
   - `[-]`: Set the second cell to 0.
   - `>`: Move the pointer to the third cell.
   - `[-]`: Set the third cell to 0.
   - `<`: Move the pointer back to the second cell.

2. **First Loop:**
   - `>+++++++++++`: Increment the third cell to 11.
   - `[<+++++++++++++>-]`: This loop will run 11 times, incrementing the second cell by 13 each time (11 * 13 = 143). The third cell will be decremented to 0 by the end of the loop.
   - `<`: Move the pointer back to the first cell.
   - `--`: Decrement the first cell by 2, setting it to -2.

3. **Output Characters:**
   - `.`: Output the character corresponding to the ASCII value of the first cell (-2). In Brainf*ck, negative values wrap around, so -2 corresponds to 254 (ÿ in extended ASCII).
   - `-----------`: Decrement the first cell by 11, setting it to -13.
   - `.`: Output the character corresponding to the ASCII value of the first cell (-13). This corresponds to 243 (ó in extended ASCII).
   - `+++++++`: Increment the first cell by 7, setting it to -6.
   - `.`: Output the character corresponding to the ASCII value of the first cell (-6). This corresponds to 250 (ú in extended ASCII).
   - `+++`: Increment the first cell by 3, setting it to -3.
   - `.`: Output the character corresponding to the ASCII value of the first cell (-3). This corresponds to 253 (ý in extended ASCII).
   - `----`: Decrement the first cell by 4, setting it to -7.
   - `.`: Output the character corresponding to the ASCII value of the first cell (-7). This corresponds to 249 (ù in extended ASCII).
   - `<`: Move the pointer back to the second cell.

The final output of the code is the sequence of characters produced by these ASCII values.
